  "prompt": "Why do American writers use yellow paper?",
  "response": "The notion that American writers use yellow paper is a common stereotype, primarily linked to the use of legal pads, which are traditionally yellow. Legal pads, invented in the late 19th century by Thomas Holley, were designed for legal professionals but became popular among writers and others due to their convenience and the fact that they were made from recycled paper.\n\nThere are a few reasons why yellow paper, specifically legal pads, became associated with American writers:\n\n1. **Visibility**: The yellow color is easier on the eyes than white and provides a good contrast with black or blue ink, making it easier to read.\n2. **Tradition**: Many writers have used legal pads out of habit or because they were following in the footsteps of other notable writers.\n3. **Practicality**: Legal pads are sturdy, portable, and the perforated pages make it easy to tear out and organize notes or drafts.\n\nWhile not all American writers use yellow paper, the association is strong enough that it has become a recognizable symbol of the writing profession in the United States.",
